{
  "text": "Geometrically, having a closed path as in the above definition means that the points v 1 , . . . , v p , and v 1 again, form the vertices of a closed figure with edges in directions parallel to {x : a i · x = 0}, i = 1, 2. An example, in R 2 , with directions parallel to the axes and p = 10, is given in Fig. 1 . In this case of m = 2 in R n a set of points has the NI-property if and only if a subset thereof forms a closed path. In Braess and Pinkus [CITATION_1] , this theorem is only stated in R 2 , but it holds in R n by the same reasoning. In this theorem, we set",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "119945051"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "119945051": {
      "title": "Interpolation by ridge functions",
      "abstract": "Abstract We consider the problem of interpolation by linear combinations of ridge functions. A ridge function is a function of the form ƒ( a · x ) where ƒ: R → R , a ∈ R d \\{ 0 } is a fixed vector, and x ∈ R d is the variable. The solvability of the interpolation problem is characterized by geometric properties."
    }
  }
}